What about sector rotation trade and business cycle.  And market liquidity, the effect of interest rate to market return. 

Which level should those go in? 

Short answer:

Business cycle basics + simple sector rotation: Level 2

Deeper sector rotation / factor & style rotation tied to macro: Level 3–4

Interest rates & market returns (discount rate, duration of equities): Level 3

Market liquidity (QT/QE, funding stress, risk-on/off regimes): Level 4–5

Let me break it down in a way that fits your “start with big picture → strategy → execution” style.

1. Business cycle & sector rotation
Where it fits
Level 2 (core concepts & simple playbook)

You’ve already got “asset allocation” and “long/short” here — business cycle & sector rotation are a perfect macro layer on top.

Level 4–5 (if you want to go into factor/style rotation & timing)

Professional-style factor rotation, cyclical vs defensive vs quality vs value based on regime belongs higher up.

How I’d split it
Level 2 version (evergreen, simple):

Concept: “The economy moves in cycles: early → mid → late → recession.”

Strategy: “Some sectors tend to do relatively better at different stages.”

Execution: “You don’t need to time perfectly; you can have a tilt not a full flip.”

Example episodes at Level 2:

“Business Cycle 101: How the Economy Drives Market Regimes”

Screen share a simple 4-phase wheel: Early, Mid, Late, Recession.

Show relative performance of broad buckets:

Early: cyclicals (industrials, consumer discretionary)

Mid: tech, growth, broad beta

Late: defensives (staples, healthcare), commodities

Recession: cash, high-quality bonds, maybe gold

Tie it back to asset allocation: “Instead of just 60/40, you think 60/40 with tilts by phase.”

“A Beginner’s Sector Rotation Playbook (Without Day Trading)”

Explain tilting via sector ETFs instead of stock picks.

E.g. “Base portfolio is 60% global equity; 20% of that equity sleeve can rotate between a small set of sector ETFs based on simple macro signals (PMI up/down, yield curve steepening/flattening).”

Keep the rules intuitive: “Growth when PMIs are rising, defensives when PMIs roll over.”

Level 4–5 version (for the nerds):

Macro indicators: ISM/PMI, leading indicators, credit spreads, yield curve.

Strategy: sector & factor rotation based on quantified signals (momentum + macro regime).

Execution: rules-based rotation among sector / factor ETFs, maybe with overlays (options, leverage).

Example higher-level episode:

“From Business Cycle to Factor Tilts: Rotating Between Growth, Value, and Quality”

Start with macro regime classification (inflation up/down, growth up/down).

Show a matrix: regime → favored factor/sector tilts.

Implement using factor ETFs (value, momentum, quality) + sector ETFs.

This fits Level 5 because it’s effectively a DIY macro/factor fund.

2. Interest rates & market returns
This is core macro literacy and should show up by Level 3 at the latest.

Where it fits
Level 1: maybe mention “higher rates = better bond yields, tougher on growth stocks” very lightly.

Level 3: full dedicated episodes – this is where it belongs as a major theme.

Level 4: link rates to volatility, carry trades, curve trades, futures.

What you’d cover at Level 3
Concepts:

Equities as long-duration assets: most of their value is in far future cash flows → more sensitive to discount rate changes.

Growth vs value: growth stocks are longer duration than value → more hit by rising rates.

Rate channels:

Discount rate ↑ → lower present value of cash flows.

Risk-free rate ↑ → higher hurdle rate → multiple compression.

Funding cost ↑ → leverage less attractive, buybacks slow, weaker companies get squeezed.

Strategies / Episodes:

“How Interest Rates Really Hit Your Portfolio (Not Just Bonds)”

Show a simple DCF (even if hand-wavy visually) to explain why higher discount rate → lower price.

Compare growth ETF vs value ETF performance in rising rate periods.

Tie into asset allocation: when rates rise from very low, maybe tilt towards value, shorter-duration bonds, more cash.

“Duration Isn’t Just for Bonds: What is Equity Duration?”

Use an analogy: “A high-growth tech stock is like a 30-year zero-coupon bond; a boring utility is like a 5-year note.”

Show chart of “equity duration” concept and how that interacts with rate cycles.

Execution: use sector/factor ETFs to adjust the “duration” of your equity sleeve.

At Level 4, you can then:

Talk about using rate futures or bond futures to hedge equity beta.

Use options on bond ETFs to play rate moves.

Connect rates to volatility (big rate shocks → volatility clusters).

3. Market liquidity
Liquidity is conceptually harder than “rates up/down,” so I’d place it higher:

Intro version: Level 3 (link to risk-on/risk-off, QE/QT in plain language).

Serious version: Level 4–5 (funding markets, dealer balance sheets, liquidity-driven crashes).

Level 3 version (macro narrative, simple impact)
Explain liquidity as: “How much ‘easy money’ is sloshing around willing to buy risk assets.”

Show:

QE vs QT as central bank adding/removing liquidity.

Broad liquidity proxies (central bank balance sheets, M2, etc.) and rough correlation with risk assets.

Episode idea:

“What is Market Liquidity and Why It Makes Bull Markets Feel Easy”

Show charts of Fed balance sheet vs S&P 500.

Relate high liquidity to tighter credit spreads, higher valuations.

Keep it conceptual, not quanty.

Level 4–5 version (pro-style)
Here it becomes very Macro Voices / Real Vision:

Talk about:

Funding markets: repo, dollar funding, basis trades.

Dealer balance sheet constraints (e.g. post-2008 regulations).

How liquidity shocks cause crashes (e.g. margin calls, forced selling, vol-target funds de-risking).

Link liquidity to:

Volatility (low liquidity → jumpy prices).

Cross-asset contagion (selling in one asset to meet margin in another).

Episodes:

“The Hidden Plumbing of Markets: How Liquidity Crises Trigger Selloffs”

Use case studies: 2008, 2018 Volmageddon, March 2020.

“Trading in a Liquidity Crunch: Why ‘Risk-Off’ Is Really ‘Cash-Up’”

Strategy: smaller position sizes, more cash, less leverage, use deep, liquid instruments (index futures / big ETFs) rather than small caps during stressed regimes.

This definitely feels like Level 4–5, with maybe a softer narrative primer at Level 3.

